turn.2: Common firecrest The common firecrest ("Regulus ignicapilla") also known as the firecrest, is a very small passerine bird in the kinglet family.
turn.4: It breeds in most of temperate Europe and northwestern Africa, and is partially migratory, with birds from central Europe wintering to the south and west of their breeding range.
turn.5: Do they have a separate species?
turn.6: Firecrests in the Balearic Islands and north Africa are widely recognised as a separate subspecies, but the population on Madeira, previously also treated as a subspecies, is now treated as a distinct species, the Madeira firecrest, "Regulus madeirensis".
turn.7: Are there any other interesting aspects about this article?
turn.8: A fossil ancestor of the firecrest has been identified from a single wing bone.
turn.10: This kinglet is greenish above and has whitish underparts.
turn.11: What other markings does it have?
turn.12: It has two white wingbars, a black eye stripe and a white supercilium.
